'For Europe, catching up in the digital sector should not mean deregulating at every turn'
description: Under pressure from the US, the European Commission is prepared to ease its legislation to halt its technological decline. But Brussels must resist being boxed into a choice between innovation and regulation and instead highlight its strengths, writes Le Monde columnist Stéphane Lauer.

Foreign interference: Why France is raising its voice and turning to the courts
description: Since 2023, French authorities have launched nine investigations into activities such as the posting of propaganda posters, all linked to the war in Ukraine and the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. The most recent case saw three people charged, including the founder of the pro-Russian advocacy group SOS Donbass.

headline: Jodie Foster: 'Without cinema, I would have been rigid, dry and much more solitary'
description: 'I wouldn't be where I am today if...' In this series, Le Monde interviews a figure about a decisive moment in their life. The American actress pays tribute to her mother, with whom she shared a close, almost inseparable bond for many years.

How Islamology stepped out of French academia's shadows after the 2015 jihadist attacks
description: Once a jewel of French research, Islamology began to decline in the 1980s, but the 2015 attacks forced authorities to refocus their efforts in this field of knowledge. Although the discipline has since experienced something of a revival, its recovery remains fragile, both as an academic subject and a highly political issue.

headline: Gay Talese, the last titan of the American press
description: He was a pioneer of New Journalism, a movement that transformed American journalism with a literary writing style. At 93, the author of the landmark 1966 profile 'Frank Sinatra Has a Cold,' finds his daily life increasingly constrained by old age.

headline: The last-minute fight to save Gaza's ancient archaeological treasures
description: Amid the vast destruction of the war, a small group of determined individuals fought to save Gaza's archaeological heritage. On September 10, they secured a few hours' reprieve from the Israeli army before a storage depot filled with artifacts was bombed to perform a delicate evacuation – the result of intense, high-level negotiations.
